{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641185"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:24:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:24:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17868"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17868"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115347"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10582"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17868"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97350"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10057"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24669"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115347"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDifferent tissues in the body have varying capacities to utilise fatty acids as an energy source. Some tissues preferentially use other substrates such as glucose for ATP production.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tissues utilises the largest proportion of fatty acids for ATP generation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver","Skeletal muscle","Brain","Adipose tissue","Kidney"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkeletal muscle\u003C/strong\u003E utilises the largest proportion of fatty acids for ATP generation. During periods of rest and moderate exercise, skeletal muscles rely heavily on fatty acid oxidation for energy production. This process occurs in the mitochondria, where fatty acids undergo beta-oxidation to produce acetyl-CoA, which then enters the citric acid cycle to generate ATP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E metabolises fatty acids primarily for ketone body production and gluconeogenesis rather than ATP generation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrain\u003C/strong\u003E cannot use fatty acids directly for energy due to the blood-brain barrier and relies almost exclusively on glucose. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E stores and releases fatty acids but does not significantly oxidise them for ATP production. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ekidney\u003C/strong\u003E can utilise fatty acids but does so to a much lesser extent than skeletal muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high capacity of skeletal muscle to oxidise fatty acids is supported by its abundant mitochondria and extensive vascular supply, allowing efficient uptake and metabolism of circulating fatty acids.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Skeletal muscle is the primary site of fatty acid oxidation for ATP production in the body.","During rest and moderate exercise, skeletal muscles derive most of their energy from fatty acid oxidation.","The liver metabolises fatty acids primarily for ketogenesis rather than ATP production."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 69; pg. 858.","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952.","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97350"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17868"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97350"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:35:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:35:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10582"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115347"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculos